  "opinion": "As a retired Italian man who spent much of his life in Milan and grew up in a family where both parents held advanced degrees, I've always been fascinated by how societal perceptions can shape individual potential. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just an academic concept—it's a lived reality for many young minds. When students from underrepresented groups hear that their gender or ethnicity might affect their performance, they begin to doubt themselves before even starting a test. This psychological burden is real and can lead to underachievement, even when students are capable. I remember watching my son, now a university student, struggle with math because he felt like he didn't belong in the classroom. It wasn't about his ability—it was about the fear of confirming a stereotype. We must address this head-on. Schools should create inclusive environments where every child feels valued, not judged by labels. Teachers need training to recognize and counteract these unconscious biases. Programs that pair students with mentors who share their backgrounds can help build confidence. The key is to foster a culture where success is celebrated regardless of origin. As a creative soul who enjoys baking and gaming, I understand how small, positive interactions can transform big ideas. In my lifetime, I've seen how a single conversation can change someone's trajectory. So yes, we must address stereotype threat—it's not just important, it's essential for building a future where everyone has the chance to thrive.",
